<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-582-879  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 582 879.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 2 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Moscow: digital maps of U.S.S.R. being developed.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tchashchin, Kirill.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Soviet UnionProduct DevelopmentResearch and DevelopmentMaps.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MOSCOW: DIGITAL MAPS OF U.S.S.R.andP;  BEING DEVELOPED MOSCOW, U.S.S.R., 1990 NOV2 (NB) -- A group of Soviet companies are developing a system to convertSoviet maps into digital form.andP;  The company's representatives claim thatl:1,000,000 maps of the U.S.S.R.andP;  will be available in computer form during1992.andM;The work to develop digital map storage and processing is being performed bya group of companies including Moscow-based ASUAS, Kartographiya mappingproduction amalgamation, and Antares company.andP;  During the MunicipalInformation Technologies show in Moscow they presented a tool for enteringmaps into computers and building geographical databases.andM;Kartographiya's deputy general director, Mr Mark Beletsky, told Newsbytesthat there are plans to enter all the Soviet Union's 22 million squarekilometers, recorded on surface maps, into machine- readable form.andP;  Theyestimates a sheet representing a reduction of 1:1,000,000 will result in a 5megabyte file and the scanning and editing process will cost as much as10,000 rubles per sheet with one third of sum attributed to equipment costs.andM;He said also that software development tools they are showing to municipalexecutives can help in the production of some very helpful databases withwide spectrum of data which can be put directly on the map.andP;  In addition, hesaid, the software provides for many sorting and retrieving options.andM;The software is still under development and not available commercially rightnow although it can be shipped custom-tailored with maps of different regionsentered into computer, Mr Beletsky concluded.andM;(Kirill Tchashchin/19901101/Press contact: Mark Beletsky, Kartographiya,phone +7 095 177-3701)</TEXT></DOC>